00:03:14.390 --> 00:03:19.360
Well, starting at the 10,000 foot level,
what is it about help?

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:22.410
What role does help
play in an application?

00:03:22.830 --> 00:03:25.300
Well,
it's one part of the documentation suite.

00:03:25.400 --> 00:03:27.860
And what do I mean by
a documentation suite?

00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:29.850
Well, I have a very broad view of that.

00:03:29.920 --> 00:03:31.760
You see,
the documentation suite is everything

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:36.620
you include with your product that
helps users understand how to use it.

00:03:36.620 --> 00:03:41.200
You might have a printed manual,
on-screen help certainly, a tutorial,

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:43.040
a read me, your website.

00:03:43.370 --> 00:03:47.110
All of those things contribute to user
experience and to the user education.

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:49.380
But so does the UI of the application.

00:03:49.450 --> 00:03:54.150
Help tags, error messages, dialogues,
and the UI itself communicates

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:56.430
to people how to use your app.

00:03:56.460 --> 00:04:00.170
So that's a pretty broad
collection of things.

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:01.620
So let's focus on help.

00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:04.230
I mean, every one of those has something
that it brings to the party

00:04:04.240 --> 00:04:05.580
for helping users understand.

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.320
But since we're here to
talk about on-screen help,

00:04:07.320 --> 00:04:09.670
let's look at that specifically.

00:04:10.460 --> 00:04:12.700
So what is the role of help?

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:15.520
What does it provide that some
of those other things don't?

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:18.710
Well, for one thing,
it's a companion to the computer.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.340
When you're using an
on-screen help system,

00:04:20.340 --> 00:04:24.570
you know that your user has a computer in
front of them and has your application.

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:28.780
That isn't necessarily true for
those other things I mentioned.

00:04:29.680 --> 00:04:31.500
Why do people use help?

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:33.790
Well, often it's a last resort for users.

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:37.170
Now, not everybody uses help this way,
but many do.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:38.360
And in fact, I do myself.

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:41.380
I have a little story to illustrate this.

00:04:41.460 --> 00:04:42.810
I think you'll find that
as you think about it,

00:04:42.810 --> 00:04:44.760
this might be how you use help as well.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:48.290
So this was a couple weeks ago,
and I just made a CD with iTunes.

00:04:48.290 --> 00:04:50.920
I burned some of my
favorite songs on a CD,

00:04:51.020 --> 00:04:52.860
and I wanted to make a CD label.

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:55.790
So I launched Illustrator,
and I drew a couple of circles,

00:04:55.790 --> 00:05:00.420
figured out how big they needed to be,
typed my song titles in and so on.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:02.730
And on the label,
I wanted a title for the CD,

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:06.050
but I wanted the title to
kind of curve around and match

00:05:06.220 --> 00:05:08.360
the roundness of the label.

00:05:08.360 --> 00:05:09.970
And I didn't know how to do that.

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:13.820
I'd never taken text and
set it on a curve before.

00:05:13.820 --> 00:05:14.930
So how did I approach the task?

00:05:15.130 --> 00:05:19.230
Well, I looked through all the menus,
and I tried out the various tools,

00:05:19.230 --> 00:05:20.900
and tried to figure out how to do it.

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:23.700
I brought all my experience
to bear with Illustrator to

00:05:23.700 --> 00:05:27.410
try and tackle this problem,
and I failed.

00:05:27.770 --> 00:05:30.500
So my next step was to find
somebody else who might know.

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:34.560
I looked around me, among my colleagues,
and asked a few questions.

00:05:34.560 --> 00:05:36.600
Hey, does anybody know how to do this?

00:05:36.610 --> 00:05:39.080
And it turns out they didn't know either.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:41.360
So at that point, I had two choices.

00:05:41.360 --> 00:05:46.080
I could give up and decide, well,
who cares if the text is curved?

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:48.450
Or I could turn to the documentation,
turn to the help,

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:51.260
and try and find my answer,
which is what I did.

00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:52.970
And I got in there,
and I found my answer.

00:05:53.210 --> 00:05:54.580
And it was a springboard for me.

00:05:54.580 --> 00:05:59.520
I was back working in Illustrator,
completing the label the way I wanted to.

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:00.180
And it was great.

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:02.410
It was a very good help experience.

00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:04.360
and that's how many users come to help.

00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:09.220
So what can you do to your help system
to optimize that kind of experience?

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:11.190
It's an important role.

00:06:11.290 --> 00:06:13.770
There are a couple
principles you can follow.

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:19.940
How do you optimize your help system
for providing a great user experience?

00:06:19.980 --> 00:06:22.780
Well, you should consider thinking
about a minimalist approach.

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:24.880
Now,
if you're an instructional design person,

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:27.550
you know that minimalism is this
entire school of thought and it

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:30.560
has a lot of principles and some
baggage associated with it as well.

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:32.920
But I'm not going to go into all of that.

00:06:32.950 --> 00:06:35.570
There's really three principles
that I have from that school of

00:06:35.570 --> 00:06:37.520
thought that I want to talk about.

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:40.350
And if you're not familiar with this,
don't think of minimalism as

00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:42.200
meaning don't provide any help.

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:44.100
That's not what it means at all.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:46.490
It sounds like it from the name, I know.

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:50.590
So what you want to do is you
want to focus on real-world tasks.

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:52.890
People come to the help
with a task in mind.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:55.530
In my case, it was curving text.

00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:59.400
I wasn't looking for help on
using the Fit to Path tool.

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.600
You want to emphasize troubleshooting.

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:05.720
Because people reach an impasse, right,
they've tried to figure it out,

00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:07.980
they've asked for help, they couldn't,
they come to the help

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:09.400
with the documentation.

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:10.600
There's a problem.

00:07:10.600 --> 00:07:12.570
They want to get on with their work.

00:07:12.840 --> 00:07:16.400
So include troubleshooting
information in your help.

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:19.320
Now separate troubleshooting sections
are all fine and well and good,

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:22.400
but if you can include troubleshooting
information with your task instructions,

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:23.610
it's even better.

00:07:24.190 --> 00:07:26.470
Because that's where people
are likely to find them and

00:07:26.470 --> 00:07:28.230
likely to encounter the problem.

00:07:29.730 --> 00:07:33.700
Another principle you can use is
acknowledging prior experience.

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:36.190
Now, I know all the authors out
there do audience analysis,

00:07:36.190 --> 00:07:38.730
and they think about, you know,
who am I writing for?

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:41.080
Who's the person who's using this?

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:44.740
Well, apply that principle down
to the very task level.

00:07:44.760 --> 00:07:49.310
Think about the topic you're describing,
the type of person who wants to do this.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:50.360
For example,

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:52.860
Someone who's coming to the
help and looking for information

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:56.830
about making a font italic,
probably a novice user.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.240
They need a certain level of instruction.

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:02.170
Someone who's coming to the help and
looking for information on kerning

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:04.820
pairs is probably an advanced user.

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:07.900
They bring a lot to the
table about font technology.

00:08:07.940 --> 00:08:10.820
Acknowledge that as you
provide instructions.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:14.720
We've all had the experience of turning
to a help system and finding the

00:08:15.210 --> 00:08:18.010
information there either too basic or--

00:08:18.300 --> 00:08:42.200
[Transcript missing]

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:47.500
Another high-level principle you can
use is to exploit the environment.

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:51.300
The on-screen help system is
on-screen and on the computer.

00:08:51.300 --> 00:08:52.340
It's not a printed book.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:55.190
You can do things in on-screen help that
you couldn't dream of doing in print,

00:08:55.630 --> 00:09:00.210
such as providing automations and
using animated graphics and so on.

00:09:00.500 --> 00:09:04.780
Likewise related to books,
it's kind of easy to find stuff in books.

00:09:04.820 --> 00:09:05.560
We know how to do that.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:08.860
You riffle through pages
and you flip through things.

00:09:08.950 --> 00:09:10.100
On-screen help, you can't do that.

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:12.630
You need to think about the structure
and making things easy to find

00:09:12.630 --> 00:09:14.420
so people can locate information.

00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:16.940
It turns out that search is
a really good way to do that.

00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:22.410
And we're going to talk about some of
the search technology we have built

00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:22.410
into Apple Help to help you with that.

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:26.430
And finally, when you write your tasks,
write for following along.

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:29.790
Assume the user is following the
instructions you're giving them.

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:32.510
A book has to be very
narrative in its nature,

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:33.160
right?

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:35.640
Because the reader might be
on a train or on the beach,

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:38.060
might not have a computer with them.

00:09:38.070 --> 00:09:41.330
And so when you look at a book,
it needs to provide task instructions

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:44.610
and kind of a narrative of what's
happening on screen as you're doing these

00:09:44.860 --> 00:09:47.520
things to keep everything in context.

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:50.770
When you're on a computer,
the user has probably come with a problem

00:09:50.770 --> 00:09:53.770
and is following your instructions along.

00:09:53.770 --> 00:09:57.530
If the UI speaks to the user
and enforces conditions such as

00:09:57.660 --> 00:10:01.460
clicking OK or making sure a value
has been specified and so on,

00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:03.390
let the user interface do that.

00:10:03.470 --> 00:10:07.540
Take advantage of those other pieces
of the documentation suite that are

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:09.770
available because you're on the computer.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:12.620
Help tags, for example,
error messages and so on.

00:10:12.710 --> 00:10:18.400
It's not necessary to be as narrative
in on-screen help as it is in a book.

00:10:21.590 --> 00:10:24.760
So, yeah,
I know what some of you are thinking.

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:27.500
That's all well and good,
but I've already written a help system,

00:10:27.530 --> 00:10:28.740
right?

00:10:28.810 --> 00:10:29.910
That's fine.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.680
There's still something you
can do to make sure your help

00:10:32.850 --> 00:10:35.580
really hits the mark on Mac OS X.

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.520
And to do that,
you just need to provide a consistent

00:10:38.520 --> 00:10:40.860
help experience and adopt Apple Help.

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:45.220
As John mentioned,
it is the help system for the platform.

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:48.160
We've worked hard to make sure the
help system is optimized for delivering

00:10:48.160 --> 00:10:49.830
on-screen information like this.

00:10:49.930 --> 00:10:52.220
We've built in some special features
that you're going to hear about today.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.840
So that's one thing you can do to
join the platform and make sure that

00:10:57.840 --> 00:10:59.290
the user has a consistent experience.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.100
You know,
John mentioned in his talk yesterday at

00:11:01.100 --> 00:11:07.070
the Adopting Aqua guideline-- Adopting
Aqua session that using custom controls

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:10.090
that don't go with the rest of the
UI can be confusing for people because

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:13.720
they come to your app and they're like,
oh, well, gee, what are these?

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:16.080
Well, a similar situation
happens with the help.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:20.860
If you roll your own help solution
and don't use the help viewer,

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:23.310
when your customer comes
and looks up the help,

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:25.350
they're coming with a task in mind.

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:27.680
But they open the help system and
they see what you've created and

00:11:27.680 --> 00:11:31.230
then immediately their task becomes
figuring that out instead of getting

00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:33.190
the answer to their question.

00:11:35.260 --> 00:11:39.140
So I've talked about the features of
Apple Help and how we try to optimize

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:40.290
it for the on-screen environment.

