00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:46.870
So we've talked about how help can be
a benefit to users in providing a good,

00:16:46.900 --> 00:16:51.560
consistent user instruction
experience on Mac OS X.

00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:55.910
But what are the benefits for
you as authors and developers?

00:16:56.340 --> 00:16:58.100
Well, it's very easy to author.

00:16:58.130 --> 00:17:00.090
Apple's embracing open
standards everywhere,

00:17:00.090 --> 00:17:01.960
as you're hearing
throughout this conference.

00:17:02.030 --> 00:17:03.250
And Help is another example.

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:04.980
We use standard HTML.

00:17:05.110 --> 00:17:08.290
You can author Apple Help with any
HTML authoring tool you choose.

00:17:08.710 --> 00:17:12.080
Anything from a Go Live or
a Dreamweaver to BBEdit to

00:17:12.080 --> 00:17:14.840
Stickies to whatever you choose.

00:17:14.840 --> 00:17:16.200
Something on another platform.

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:20.640
Whatever you use to author HTML today,
you can continue to use with Apple Help.

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:23.020
It's also very easy to implement.

00:17:23.020 --> 00:17:25.160
These features we just
saw in the Help Viewer,

00:17:25.250 --> 00:17:28.460
the internet connection, the searching,
all of that is provided

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:29.760
by the Help Viewer.

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:32.330
There isn't anything special that
you have to do as an author to

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:33.860
enable those or make those work.

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:37.040
And most importantly,
it's one help solution for Mac OS X.

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:39.060
Carbon, Cocoa, it doesn't matter.

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:42.050
You can adopt it and deploy
it with your application.

00:17:46.980 --> 00:17:50.100
So let's look at the
specs for the system.

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:51.840
It renders HTML 3.2.

00:17:51.840 --> 00:17:54.520
That's without JavaScript or forms.

00:17:54.540 --> 00:17:56.280
Natively plays QuickTime movies.

00:17:56.290 --> 00:17:58.740
You saw an example of a
Flash movie playing in there.

00:17:58.740 --> 00:18:01.020
But you can use any
QuickTime media you want to.

00:18:01.070 --> 00:18:05.230
QuickTime supports over 200
different media formats-- JPEG,

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:06.290
GIF.

00:18:06.770 --> 00:18:10.980
Flash, MP3, you name it,
basically QuickTime can play it and

00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:12.800
you can use it in your help system.

00:18:12.820 --> 00:18:15.040
And again,
by saying we play QuickTime natively,

00:18:15.040 --> 00:18:17.830
I mean we do not use
the QuickTime plugin.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:19.700
We use the Sherlock Engine for searching.

00:18:19.790 --> 00:18:23.080
That's how we get our fast
searching and our relevancy ranking.

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:26.200
You can launch AppleScript from
a simple hyperlink.

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:28.460
We'll get into the syntax of that later.

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.560
And you can retrieve
content from the internet.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:35.540
The Help Center that you saw displays all
the books that's available for the user.

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:37.500
This is based on permissions.

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:40.380
If the user does not have permission
to launch your application,

00:18:40.410 --> 00:18:42.440
your help does not show
up in the Help Center.

00:18:42.560 --> 00:18:46.090
That way users are insured of seeing
reference material only for applications

00:18:46.100 --> 00:18:48.660
that they're actually able to use.

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:53.420
And if you're familiar with
Apple Help from Mac OS 9 and Mac OS 8.5,

00:18:53.420 --> 00:18:55.540
where it started,
you'll be pleased to know that

00:18:55.540 --> 00:18:58.760
you no longer have to store your
help in one single location.

00:18:58.780 --> 00:19:02.200
It works seamlessly with help stored
on the network or on the hard disk and,

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:04.450
of course, on the internet.

00:19:08.170 --> 00:19:10.210
So I'd like to talk a little bit
more about this internet-based

00:19:10.210 --> 00:19:13.120
content because it's a very
important feature of the Help Viewer,

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.560
and it doesn't work like
it does in a web browser.

00:19:15.790 --> 00:19:18.290
You might think it does,
but it behaves differently,

00:19:18.350 --> 00:19:19.740
and let's look at it.

00:19:22.100 --> 00:19:24.160
So the help viewer prefers local content.

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:25.650
It always looks locally first.

00:19:25.740 --> 00:19:27.940
And by locally,
I mean in your help folder with

00:19:27.940 --> 00:19:29.590
the rest of your materials.

00:19:29.650 --> 00:19:32.280
If it can't find it there,
if that file is missing,

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:34.030
then it will look in a cache folder.

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:37.640
Every user has a help cache and
the help cache contains files

00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:39.470
that were recently downloaded.

00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:42.490
If it doesn't find them
in the user's help cache,

00:19:42.490 --> 00:19:46.840
then it goes to your site and
retrieves the page using HTTP.

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:50.280
Now you tell us where you're going
to put this content on the Internet.

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:54.020
You give us the URL to
pre-append to the location there

00:19:54.020 --> 00:19:56.360
when you index your content.

00:19:56.910 --> 00:20:01.010
and once we do download a file,
it's cached locally for three days.

00:20:01.010 --> 00:20:03.780
That way users can come back and
look at it again without having

00:20:03.780 --> 00:20:07.560
to reconnect to the Internet,
but it doesn't stick along so, you know,

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:11.030
stay around so long that it's stale
and in the meantime you may have

00:20:11.030 --> 00:20:12.240
updated what's on the Internet.

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:17.060
I have a little illustration
here to demonstrate this.

00:20:17.060 --> 00:20:19.760
So the simplest scenario,
a page is requested,

00:20:19.760 --> 00:20:23.910
it looks on the disk and it finds it,
and so the help viewer opens the page.

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:26.200
If it does not find it
in your help folder,

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:28.830
it looks in the cache,
and if it finds it there,

00:20:28.830 --> 00:20:30.410
it opens it from the cache.

00:20:30.410 --> 00:20:34.400
If it does not find it in the cache,
it uses HTTP to go to your remote site,

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:37.880
and it takes the page, downloads it,
and puts it in the cache,

00:20:37.890 --> 00:20:39.900
and loads it from there.

00:20:39.900 --> 00:20:41.100
Now I keep saying page.

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:43.810
That's not quite right,
because this happens for every

00:20:43.810 --> 00:20:44.900
element that's on the page.

00:20:44.900 --> 00:20:47.890
If you have graphics,
the same process is repeated.

00:20:47.920 --> 00:20:50.790
It will look locally,
it will look in the cache,

00:20:50.850 --> 00:20:53.900
it will look on the Internet and
retrieve it if necessary.

00:20:54.060 --> 00:20:57.260
That way you can have a mix of
local graphics with remote pages,

00:20:57.370 --> 00:21:00.890
or local pages with remote graphics,
or all one or the other.

00:21:00.900 --> 00:21:02.900
It's very flexible in that regard.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:06.220
And as an author,
you don't have to decide or even know

00:21:06.220 --> 00:21:08.900
where those pieces are going to reside.

00:21:08.900 --> 00:21:12.900
You make that choice at the very last
minute when you ship your product.

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:14.900
And that's one of the
key advantages of this.

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:16.900
And you guys know what
development cycles are,

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:17.900
right?

00:21:17.900 --> 00:21:20.750
Your application engineers
are creating their apps,

00:21:20.890 --> 00:21:23.100
coding madly,
and your help team or your help

00:21:23.100 --> 00:21:26.900
person is following shortly behind,
lagging, trying to catch up.

00:21:26.900 --> 00:21:28.960
At some point, the help has to freeze.

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:30.410
You have to ship the product.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:33.430
It goes off, it's done,
but development can continue,

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.890
and often does continue after that point.

00:21:35.890 --> 00:21:37.810
Bugs will be fixed or introduced.

00:21:38.100 --> 00:21:40.770
Features will change and so on.

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:42.900
And that makes the help wrong.

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:46.880
And having a help that's incomplete
or incorrect isn't good for anyone.

00:21:47.020 --> 00:21:49.950
So, when you get to that point
where you need to freeze,

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:52.810
you can take a snapshot and say,
"What features of this

00:21:52.980 --> 00:21:54.820
product are likely to change?"

00:21:56.560 --> 00:21:59.690
take the topics that cover those
features and put them on the internet.

00:21:59.690 --> 00:22:02.770
That allows you to be able to
maintain them after the product

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:05.500
is released or at least catch
up right before it's released.

00:22:05.500 --> 00:22:08.360
And as an author,
you don't have to decide up until that

00:22:08.370 --> 00:22:12.160
very moment because the help viewer,
as we've seen, looks in these places

00:22:12.310 --> 00:22:13.780
and finds the content.

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:15.370
It's like a hunting dog.

00:22:15.400 --> 00:22:18.200
It'll sniff it out and find
it in any of these locations.

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:22.420
You don't need to make sure that all
of your hrefs are pointing to specific

00:22:22.470 --> 00:22:24.490
folder names or specific sites.

00:22:24.490 --> 00:22:27.500
It handles figuring that out for you.

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:35.450
So how do you author Apple Help?

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:39.030
Well, it's really easy.

00:22:39.150 --> 00:22:42.360
You start with HTML.

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:43.590
Again, HTML

00:22:44.150 --> 00:22:47.540
You take your start page,
the main page for your help book.

00:22:47.550 --> 00:22:50.450
That might be your table of contents,
your quick clicks page

00:22:50.450 --> 00:22:51.460
as we saw in our demo.

00:22:51.460 --> 00:22:54.320
Whatever page you consider to
be main for your help book.

00:22:54.320 --> 00:22:55.910
And you modify it.

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:57.260
You add one line.

00:22:57.300 --> 00:22:58.190
You add a meta tag.

00:22:58.190 --> 00:23:00.550
A meta tag is a standard HTML element.

00:23:00.550 --> 00:23:04.630
Put a meta tag of the type Apple title
and the name of your help book.

00:23:04.630 --> 00:23:06.850
In this example, myapp.help.

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:08.700
Add that to your one page.

00:23:08.730 --> 00:23:11.450
This is a standard element so other
systems are going to ignore it.

00:23:11.630 --> 00:23:14.040
You can continue to deploy this
information on other systems.

00:23:14.100 --> 00:23:16.290
systems, no problem.

00:23:16.770 --> 00:23:17.600
And that's it.

00:23:17.600 --> 00:23:19.940
That's the only modification
you have to make.

00:23:20.110 --> 00:23:22.840
You take your entire help folder
and you drag and drop it on top

00:23:22.840 --> 00:23:25.490
of the Apple Help indexing tool.

00:23:25.730 --> 00:23:29.220
The indexing tool scans all of
your content and creates a search

00:23:29.220 --> 00:23:33.160
index and puts it in the correct
place in the folder for you.

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:34.740
So you want to do this at the end, right?

00:23:34.760 --> 00:23:37.010
Because you want your
help to be up to date.

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:40.560
You want that search index to
represent the latest content

00:23:40.610 --> 00:23:42.590
that you have in there.

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:45.670
When you index your content,
this is also where you specify where

00:23:45.670 --> 00:23:50.160
that remote site's going to be if
you're using Internet-based content.

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:52.300
And this is also where you
turn on anchor indexing.

00:23:52.300 --> 00:23:55.120
Now, we haven't talked about anchors yet,
but we will in a moment.

00:23:55.220 --> 00:23:59.010
Just keep in mind that it's at index
time when you turn this feature on or

00:23:59.010 --> 00:24:01.660
off to decide you're going to use it.

00:24:04.290 --> 00:24:06.200
So you've created your help,
where do you put it?

00:24:06.260 --> 00:24:09.010
Well, on Mac OS X,
help resides inside your

00:24:09.010 --> 00:24:10.740
applications bundle.

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:13.500
All the localized help can live there,
just like all the other localized

00:24:13.540 --> 00:24:15.170
resources with Mac OS X.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:19.290
And this provides a nice drag-and-drop
install of your application

00:24:19.420 --> 00:24:21.030
and all of its help files.

00:24:23.410 --> 00:24:25.440
How do people get to your help?

00:24:25.440 --> 00:24:27.120
Well, three ways primarily.

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:29.860
The first method of access,
and the one you should

00:24:29.860 --> 00:24:31.840
definitely implement,
is a help menu.

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:34.540
At a help menu,
we recommend a single item in there.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:36.810
In this case,
it's Mail Help in this slide.

00:24:36.860 --> 00:24:39.600
It should obviously be
your application's name,

00:24:39.710 --> 00:24:43.590
Help, with a command question mark
as the keyboard shortcut.

00:24:43.630 --> 00:24:45.550
So why do we recommend one item?

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:48.800
Well, you know, in user tests,
it's interesting.

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:48.800
We've

00:24:49.650 --> 00:24:51.730
I've sat through many
user tests at Apple,

00:24:51.730 --> 00:24:54.840
and we find that when people have a long,
complicated help menu,

00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:58.630
especially when those items in the menu
kind of all lead to the same place,

00:24:58.630 --> 00:24:59.190
right?

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:01.000
They all open the help
system and they go somewhere.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:04.480
I know as authors, it's painful to admit,
but to a lot of people,

00:25:04.480 --> 00:25:06.050
it's all kind of the same.

00:25:06.050 --> 00:25:10.610
If there's four items in the help menu,
we'll often see people pick the

00:25:10.610 --> 00:25:12.850
wrong item five times in a row.

00:25:12.850 --> 00:25:16.010
Yeah, you stand back there
behind the glass and say,

00:25:16.010 --> 00:25:17.940
no, how can you be doing this?

00:25:18.190 --> 00:25:18.680
But it's true.

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:21.180
A nice, simple menu works great.

00:25:21.230 --> 00:25:23.310
And when people have questions,
they just want to get to where

00:25:23.310 --> 00:25:24.260
they're going to get their answers.

00:25:26.260 --> 00:25:29.340
You can also implement a Help button,
which is the second graphic there.

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:32.940
This is a great way to
provide contextual help.

00:25:33.110 --> 00:25:36.900
And from the contextual menu as well,
you can add a help item there.

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:39.280
If you're going to do provide
contextual help with a

00:25:39.310 --> 00:25:42.220
Help button or a contextual menu,
you normally want to

00:25:42.260 --> 00:25:45.490
use an anchor to do so,
and we'll talk about that.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.700
So essentially,
we've covered everything you need

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:55.860
to do from the authoring side
to get your help up and running.

00:25:55.890 --> 00:25:56.940
But what else can you do?

00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.710
If you have some extra time or you
want to go that little extra step to

00:25:59.720 --> 00:26:04.200
provide a really good help experience,
there are a few things you

00:26:04.200 --> 00:26:07.760
can do and take advantage of
some of our advanced features.

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:12.490
and I are here today to talk about how to
provide on-screen help for Mac OS users.

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:14.570
In this session,
we will talk about how to provide

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:16.090
on-screen help for Mac OS users.

00:26:39.180 --> 00:26:42.070
We set up some user studies.

00:26:42.780 --> 00:26:48.280
Earlier in the study,
we had someone do a task and they had to

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:50.620
come to the help for information on it.

00:26:50.620 --> 00:26:54.790
We provided an automation that would
actually do that task for them.

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:58.540
and 95%, maybe 99%, I think it
was one person out of the group,

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:00.350
chose to do the automation.

00:27:00.420 --> 00:27:03.270
Rather than doing the task themselves,
they clicked, yeah, do it for me.

00:27:03.320 --> 00:27:05.600
I mean, come on,
that's what computers are supposed to do,

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:05.980
right?

00:27:06.120 --> 00:27:06.950
Do things for me.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:10.570
Well, later in the same study,
we had another task,

00:27:10.570 --> 00:27:13.270
and in order to successfully
complete that task,

00:27:13.300 --> 00:27:17.100
they had to undo what this
automation had done for them earlier.

00:27:17.120 --> 00:27:20.120
We wanted to see if people were
going to become reliant upon that

00:27:20.120 --> 00:27:23.560
automation and go back to it or
be stumped when confronted with

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:25.390
having how do I undo this thing.

00:27:25.400 --> 00:27:28.270
And it turns out that nobody
had any problems with that.

00:27:28.300 --> 00:27:31.010
Using the automation did not
impede their ability to learn

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:32.940
how to work with the system.

00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:35.470
And in talking with them after the study,
they loved it.

00:27:35.620 --> 00:27:37.650
They wanted more of that type of thing.

00:27:37.660 --> 00:27:40.490
So this is a great opportunity
to make your help stand out.

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:46.400
You can also improve search results.

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:48.960
We talked earlier about how it
can be difficult to find things

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:50.540
in an on-screen help system.

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:53.410
One of the best ways to
find things is by searching.

00:27:53.530 --> 00:27:55.680
Come to help with a
representation of your task,

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:58.630
type in your question,
and get a related list of topics.

00:27:58.630 --> 00:28:02.050
Now, to make that work,
it's up to you as an author to provide

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:07.110
keywords that are going to relate your
tasks to real-world representations.

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:09.030
You can use the keyword
meta tag for that.

00:28:09.190 --> 00:28:13.400
You can also use keywords to
provide synonyms and misspellings.

00:28:13.570 --> 00:28:15.390
For example,
we spell QuickTime a couple of

00:28:15.470 --> 00:28:19.120
ways in our help content usually to
make sure that people can find it.

00:28:19.450 --> 00:28:22.680
Because believe it or not,
people do want to spell it as two words,

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:24.940
unusually.

00:28:26.100 --> 00:28:27.880
You can also use the robots meta tag.

00:28:27.880 --> 00:28:30.940
This is a standard tag if you run a
website and you're familiar with it.

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:34.180
But this provides you with a way to
omit a page from a search result.

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:37.960
So that page will not come up
when somebody searches for a term.

00:28:39.290 --> 00:28:41.340
So why would you want to do that?

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:45.680
Well, if you have a table of contents
page or a Quick Clicks page,

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:48.700
all of the words on that page
are going to get indexed.

00:28:48.770 --> 00:28:52.080
And when a user types in those words,
they'll see that as a result.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:54.690
And if they go to it,
it doesn't really help them, right?

00:28:54.700 --> 00:28:56.500
It's just the table of contents.

00:28:56.500 --> 00:28:58.460
It's kind of being a tease.

00:28:58.760 --> 00:29:01.150
So you use robots to omit
that page from searching.

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:03.350
And that way, when people search,
they get the pages with

00:29:03.350 --> 00:29:05.560
the real content on them.

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:10.900
Apple Abstract is another
meta tag that we support.

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:14.310
Add this to your content
with the contents of this tag

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:17.190
being a summary of the page.

00:29:17.720 --> 00:29:21.400
When that page is found by a search,
that summary will appear

00:29:21.400 --> 00:29:23.240
underneath the topic title.

00:29:23.480 --> 00:29:25.620
This lets users get an idea
of what's on that page,

00:29:25.620 --> 00:29:29.560
a little short paragraph
describing what they're going

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:31.040
to learn if they click on that.

00:29:31.050 --> 00:29:35.140
It makes search results a little bit
more usable because they can decide.

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:38.870
And if your content is on the Internet,
it's even better because then they can

00:29:38.870 --> 00:29:43.740
decide and make a more educated choice
when they go to download that page.

00:29:49.430 --> 00:29:51.080
Anchor Lookup.

00:29:51.080 --> 00:29:53.280
An anchor is a standard HTML element.

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:54.940
It's not visible to the user.

00:29:54.940 --> 00:29:56.910
It's contained in the HTML code.

00:29:57.010 --> 00:30:02.670
It's usually a short little phrase
or a name such as printing 001.

00:30:02.760 --> 00:30:07.570
Anchors are how you provide access
to specific pages of the help.

00:30:07.990 --> 00:30:10.580
As an author,
you add this anchor to your page.

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:14.240
You turn on anchor indexing
when you index your content.

00:30:14.370 --> 00:30:18.050
And then your application can display a
page in the help simply by telling the

00:30:18.060 --> 00:30:20.660
help viewer to open this anchor name.

00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:23.170
The application doesn't
know what page it's on.

00:30:23.200 --> 00:30:26.280
It doesn't have to know what folder
it's in or any of its location.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:32.090
It just says, "Hey, help viewer,
show me the page with printing

00:30:32.090 --> 00:30:32.090
001 on it," and it'll happen.

00:30:35.790 --> 00:30:37.990
Remote content,
we've talked about this a little bit.

00:30:38.090 --> 00:30:40.740
This is a great way to help
users and a great way to

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:43.040
keep your content up to date,
as I've said.

00:30:43.110 --> 00:30:46.170
If you're gonna implement it,
here's a couple things to keep in mind.

00:30:46.400 --> 00:30:48.500
You want to optimize your
pages for downloading.

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:50.690
Now, a lot of help is text,
and so they're small and

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:52.120
they come down quickly.

00:30:52.160 --> 00:30:55.470
But if you're using graphics,
consider putting the graphics local

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:57.670
so they don't have to be downloaded.

00:30:57.750 --> 00:31:00.480
Again,
the Help Viewer will manage that for you.

00:31:00.580 --> 00:31:03.240
Or use QuickTime Reference Movies.

00:31:03.280 --> 00:31:05.450
And of course, in QuickTime,
movies is what they

00:31:05.450 --> 00:31:06.480
call their file format.

00:31:06.480 --> 00:31:07.700
It can be a JPEG or a GIF.

00:31:07.700 --> 00:31:09.770
It doesn't have to be an animation.

00:31:09.910 --> 00:31:12.550
But a reference movie is very small,
just a couple of K.

00:31:12.800 --> 00:31:14.520
The Help Viewer will download that.

00:31:14.540 --> 00:31:17.580
And because it has the graphic
that's referred to in the HTML,

00:31:17.580 --> 00:31:21.310
will display the entire page
right away very quickly.

00:31:21.410 --> 00:31:23.760
Then QuickTime will see
that it's a reference movie.

00:31:23.790 --> 00:31:26.750
And QuickTime will go out on the
network and download the graphic

00:31:26.750 --> 00:31:28.620
that actually appears there.

00:31:28.680 --> 00:31:30.600
Just a little tip for you.

00:31:30.600 --> 00:31:32.600
We've talked about searching.

00:31:32.620 --> 00:31:35.100
If you're going to use remote content,
it's even more important to optimize

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:38.480
for searching because you don't want
people to hit the Internet too often.

00:31:38.710 --> 00:31:43.570
Try and limit the topics per page and
make your topic titles very accurate.

00:31:43.790 --> 00:31:49.190
What I mean by that,
if you have a very long page with several

00:31:49.190 --> 00:31:52.590
topics on it and you do a search for it,
only the title for that page

00:31:52.590 --> 00:31:52.590
shows up in the search results.

00:31:53.390 --> 00:31:56.400
If that title of the page doesn't
reflect the rest of the information,

00:31:56.450 --> 00:31:59.320
they might not get that that's
the page they should look at.

00:31:59.380 --> 00:32:03.310
So breaking that up into smaller
chunks helps people find stuff,

00:32:03.480 --> 00:32:05.870
and it goes to optimizing
for downloading as well.

00:32:10.060 --> 00:32:11.760
These are some help
commands you can download,

00:32:11.800 --> 00:32:12.890
excuse me, you can implement.

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:14.690
I'm not going to talk about the HTML.

00:32:14.690 --> 00:32:16.010
I won't read it to you.

